<br>
LMAO quaintly put. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
<br>
While you're at it, could you please have a *cough* <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> chat</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->with the members of your design staff in charge of assigning <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> focus</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> effects to items, and ask them to look at:<br>
<br>
- Which type of focus effect would be appropriate for the player class who would likely seek to obtain that item?<br>
- What should be the practical lifespan of that item focus' usefulness before the person is capable of obtaining a better focus item?<br>
<br>
When considering what level (I, II, III) a focus effect should be, ask them to think about:<br>
<br>
- From what level mob did that item drop?<br>
- How long will the caster be able to make USE of that item with spells he/she will be casting AFTER aquiring the item?<br>
<br>
It is disheartening that a focus II effect would be applied to an item that casters under 44th level could not obtain without twinking. By the time someone can actually get that item himself, it won't benefit his everyday spells. <br>
<br>
Others have made this comparison and I'll reiterate it with a simple analogy:<br>
<br>
When a <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  meleer</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> gets a focus item (e.g. haste belt), that item is going to improve his damage output. When he upgrades to a new weapon, that haste is applied to how fast he swings the new weapon, hence the haste item is enhancing his effectiveness proportioinately. <br>
<br>
When a <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  caster</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> gets a focus item commensurate to his level, then upgrades his spells (often through greater time and expense than melees upgrade weapons), the caster's focus item no longer enhances his effectiveness. For all intents and purposes, the item's focus effect ceases to exist, as if he never had it at all.<br>
<br>
It would restore my faith in Verant if you'd consider changing this around as others have suggested --  so that:<br>
focus I would affect all spells 19th level and higher by X%;<br>
focus II would affect spells 29th level and higher by Y%,<br>
focus III would affect spells 44th level and higher by Z%.<br>
The various types of focus wouldn't need to change (though some of them are on the wrong items!), and the incremental percentages of enhancement could scale up from I, to II, to III, for each type of focus (e.g. enhancement haste 15%, 22%, 30%, mana preservation 10%, 15%, 20%, etc). <br>
<br>
BTW, I specified 19th and 29th purposefully... because for nearly every casting class, those spell levels offer significant boosts in power sufficient to push players towards seeking more challenging zones. <br>
<br>
